                            <p>
                                <rs type="art" ref="ar0142">view of Nanny House</rs>
                            <lb/>vastly wa<gap unit="chars" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>ted</p>
                            <p>Where put
                                <lb/>
                                <rs type="art" ref="ar0143">
                                    <persName ref="pe0113">
                                        <choice>
                                            <abbr>L<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Ch: Jus:</abbr>
                                            <expan>Lord Chief Justice Glynne</expan>
                                        </choice>
                                    </persName>
                                </rs>
                                <note type="editorial">Sir John Glynne (1603–1666), judge and politician, who negotiated successfully the turbulent years of civil war and restoration in Britain to carve out a successful career and emerge a wealthy man. Pennant's full account of his life is given in A tour in Wales, MDCCLXX, vol. 1 ([1778]), pp. 101–4, with Plate XII, 'Chief Justice Glynne', at p. 102+.</note>
                                <lb/>&amp; <placeName ref="pl1359">Fisherwick House</placeName>, <persName ref="pe0810">Donnegals</persName>
                                <note type="editorial">Fisherwick, Staffordshire, was in the ownership of Arthur Chichester, fifth earl of Donegall (1739–1799), MP for Malmesbury in Wiltshire between 1768 and 1774. History of Parliament on-line. See The journey from Chester to London (1782), p. 117: 'Passed through Fisherwick park, a fine seat of the Earl of Donnegal'. </note>
                            </p>
